 "por": {
  "por_cntn": "<div class=\"porColContainerWBG\">\n<div class=\"porContentCol\"><p>This project deals with a connection between dyamical systems and  number theory. A  dynamical system here stands for an abstract set of  points together   with an evolution law which governs the way points  move over time. It   turns out that many problems concerning  simultaneous approximation of   real numbers by rational numbers can be  understood in terms of the   behavior of certain orbits. Furthermore,  systems that arise in this   context are of algebraic nature (so-called  homogeneous spaces), which makes it possible to use a wide   variety of  sophisticated tools for their investigation.</p>\n<p><span style=\"color: #222222; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;\">One  important theme of the project was studying exceptional trajectories  and corresponding number-theoretical objects. For example divergent trajectories on the space of lattices correspond to singular systems of linear forms. Jointly with Kadyrov,&nbsp; Lindenstrauss and&nbsp; Margulis the PI estimated the Hausdorff dimension of the set of singular systems from above. Singular vectors were found on any analytic nondegenerate submanifold of R^n in the joint work with Moshchevitin and Weiss. With Mirzadeh the PI obtained an estimate for <span style=\"color: #222222; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;\">the Hausdorff dimension of the set of points in a homogeneous space whose trajectories avoid a fixed subset. This also has number-theoretic applications.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"color: #222222; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; background-color: #ffffff; display: inline !important; float: none;\"><span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: